Stocks in South Africa Climb; BHP Billiton, Richemont, DRDGold, Mondi Move

-- B y   R o b e r t   B r a n d   a n d   S i k o n a t h i   M a n t s h a n t s h a
-- 
2011-07-15T15:52:37Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-07-15/south-african-stocks-fall-for-2nd-day-led-by-anglo-american-bhp-billiton.html
The FTSE/JSE  Africa  All Share Index
climbed 84.49, or 0.3 percent, to 32,288.43 by the 5 p.m. close
in Johannesburg, taking its advance this week to 0.9 percent, a
fourth week of gains.  The following were among the most active stocks in the
South African market today.  BHP Billiton Ltd. (BHP)  , the world’s largest mining
company fell to the lowest level since June 28, slipping 3.28
rand, or 1.2 percent, to 260.20 rand. The company agreed to buy
Houston-based Petrohawk Energy Corp. for about $12.1 billion in
cash in its biggest acquisition.  Cie Financiere Richemont SA (CFR)  , a maker of luxury
watches, retreated for a second day, losing 25 cents, or 0.6
percent, to 45.35 rand. The stock was downgraded to “hold”
from “buy” at Deutsche Bank AG.  DRDGold Ltd. (DRD)  , a gold miner, tumbled the most since
May 3 after saying capital expenditure for the year ended in
June 30 is expected to rise 70 percent. The shares dropped 20
cents, or 5.9 percent, to 3.21 rand.  Harmony Gold Mining Co. (HAR SJ), Africa’s third-biggest
producer of the metal, gained 3.04 rand, or 3.2 percent, to
98.68 rand, the highest since April 29, after saying gold
production for the June quarter is likely to be 3 percent higher
than the previous quarter, even after days lost because of
public holidays.  Micromega Holdings Ltd. (MMG)  , an  investment company 
with interests ranging from lubrication equipment to financial
services, surged the most since Jan. 20, climbing 30 cents, or
24 percent, to 1.55 rand. Earnings per share excluding one-time
items for the six months to June 30 are expected to be as much
as 82 percent higher than a year earlier, it said in a
regulatory filing today.  Mondi Ltd. (MND)  ,  Europe ’s largest maker of office
paper, snapped six days of gains, slipping 1.72 rand, or 3
percent, to 55.62 rand. The stock was downgraded to “neutral,”
from “buy” at Bank of America Corp.  To contact the reporter on this story:
